And now we can create chart by using ggplot.

So I will use US economic time series data.

1st chart | Relation between personal consumption expenditures and personal savings rate.

ggplot(economics, mapping = aes(x=pce, y=psavert)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth() +
  geom_rug()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

2th chart | Relation between unemployed and personal saving rate.

ggplot(economics, mapping = aes(x=uempmed, y=psavert)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

3nd chart | Relation between saving rate and date group by decade

econ_by_decade <- economics %>% 
        mutate(decade = lubridate::year(date) %/% 10 * 10) %>% 
        group_by(decade)

ggplot(econ_by_decade, mapping = aes(x = decade, 
                         y = psavert, 
                         group = decade, 
                         fill = decade)) +
  geom_boxplot()

4rd chart | Relation between unemployed and rate group by decade.

ggplot(econ_by_decade, mapping = aes(x = decade, y = unemploy, fill = decade)) +
  geom_col()

5th chart | Relation between personal consumption expenditure and date group by decade.

ggplot(econ_by_decade, mapping = aes(x = decade, y = pce, group = decade, fill = decade)) +
  geom_boxplot()
